{"title": "Can Tech Track the Virus Without Shredding Privacy?", "link": "https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/can-tech-track-the-virus-without-shredding-privacy/2020/04/15/72b8da46-7ed0-11ea-84c2-0792d8591911_story.html?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=wp_business", "description": "When Apple Inc. and Google announced they were jointly building tools to help limit the spread of the coronavirus, a debate about the benefits of such technologies and their drawbacks suddenly became much more concrete for users in the U.S. and Europe. Countries in Asia had been turning to technology since the early days of the outbreak, including with some applications that went further in drawing on personal data.", "date": "2020-04-15", "categories": "Business", "source": "The Washington Post", "sentiment": "positive"}
{"title": "The End of Cash?", "link": "https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/energy/the-end-of-cash/2020/04/15/e8592ff6-7ee1-11ea-84c2-0792d8591911_story.html?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=wp_business", "description": "Do we still need cash? Humans have used all sorts of things as stores of value — rare metals, strings of shells, even jugs of whiskey. Over time the objects have become more ephemeral, from coins to paper to digital forms. Economists see great payoffs in a cashless society: lower costs for businesses and new tools to manage economies, stymie tax evasion and fight money laundering. Critics see an erosion of privacy, frightening new powers for governments and another sign of widening inequality.", "date": "2020-04-15", "categories": "Business", "source": "The Washington Post", "sentiment": "positive"}
